C. Carta - M. Marfoglia - T. Tuuva
EPFL-dlab
About the project
What does the title say?
Most used ingredients?
Looking for exotic food?
Time for cooking?
What about healthy food?
There are 15700 labelized recipes from 36 different regions.
One can eat only italian plates for dinner everyday for almost 7 years!
The first 10 regions make for the 45% of all recipes!
Titles need to be catchy to interest people: apparently, most users
really like chicken! We can also see that one of the words that people
use the most is 'easy':
people want recipes that are easy and fast to make.
A lot of recipes are about sweets:
cookies, cake and pie seem to enjoy a lot of attention.
Obviously all around the world people are crazy about salt and pepper!
In average, 10% of the ingredients in a recipe is salt:
the Belgian recipes are the saltiest whereas the Asian recipes are
the least with only 3% of occurences. Countries are defined by their
culture and recipes, try to identify them by their recipes' ingredients!
Are you willing to try something exotic?
Just look at this chord diagram,
it will help you find which regions
have the more similarities yet with
some differences as you have
seen right before.
We can observe some
obvious correlation in this
chord map, for example US
and Canada shares 10% of
their recipes. But if you prefer
Greek food you will surely
like Italian or Australian recipes.
By looking at the map we see a lot of disparity in the average cooking
time. German recipes takes quite a long time to cook, with their
delicious cakes and patisseries, whereas US recipes are quite quick to
realize but don't be fooled by junk food!
It is time to avoid fast-food and discover which regions offers the best
recipes for your health. Maybe you should go for a Japanese recipe,
it seems healthier but if you don't like asian food,
you should try Mediteranean or Scandinavian recipes.
This project analysed recipes coming from different websites.
As the recipes came from all over the world, the goal was to find
interesting correlations between regions, as well as hindsightful
statistics of the data.
The goal was also to create a tool which gives recipes based on
provided ingredients from the user and based on various criteria
such as health or cooking time...
